quran[18]{c,v,t,f}:
52,32,"Do their minds prompt them to say such things, or are they a people immersed in transgression?” {1}",footnotes:1:In these two sentences
52,33,"Do they say: “He has himself fabricated the Qur'an?” No; the truth is that they are altogether averse to believing. {1}",footnotes:1:In other words
52,34,"(If they are truthful in this), then let them produce a discourse of similar splendour. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
52,35,"Did they come into being without any creator? Or were they their own creators?"
52,36,"Or is it they who created the heavens and the earth? No; the truth is that they lack sure faith. {1}",footnotes:1:The questions asked before this were meant to make the disbelievers of Makkah realize that whatever they were saying to belie the Prophet Muhammad’s (peace be upon him) claim to prophethood was highly irrational. Now in this verse the question put before them is: What is that in the message of the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) which you find so embarrassing for yourselves? He just says that Allah is your Creator and you should only serve Him. Why are you annoyed at it? Are you your own creators? Or
52,37,"Or do they have your Lord's treasures in their keeping? Or have absolute authority over them? {1}",footnotes:1:This is an answer to the objection of the disbelievers of Makkah who said: Why had Muhammad (peace be upon him)
52,38,"Or do they have a ladder whereon they can climb and attempt to listen (to what is transpiring in the Higher Realm)? Then, let any of them who has listened to it produce a clear proof of it."
52,39,"Or does Allah have daughters whereas you have sons? {1}",footnotes:1:A detailed reasoning has been compressed into these brief sentences. It means to say: If you deny what the Prophet (peace be upon him) says
52,40,"Or is it that you ask of them any recompense so that they should fear to be weighed down under the burden of debt? {1}",footnotes:1:The question is actually directed to the disbelievers. It means: If the Messenger had a selfish motive and had been exerting only for a personal gain from you
52,41,"Or is it that they have access to (the Truths in) the realm beyond sense-perception which they are writing down? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
52,42,"Or are they contriving a stratagem against you? {1} If so, that stratagem will rebound against the unbelievers. {2}",footnotes:1:The allusion is to the secret plots that the disbelievers of Makkah used to devise in their meetings in order to defeat the mission of the Prophet (peace be upon him) and to kill him.|181685:This is one of the clear prophecies of the Quran. In the initial stage at Makkah when the Prophet (peace be upon him) had no apparent power and support with him except a handful of the ill-equipped Muslims and the whole nation was opposing and resisting him relentlessly
52,43,"Do they have any god other than Allah? Exalted be Allah above whatever they associate (with Him in His Divinity). {1}",footnotes:1:That is
52,44,"(So obstinate are they that) even if they were to see some fragments of the sky falling down they would still say: “It is only a mass of cloud.” {1}",footnotes:1:This is meant to expose the stubbornness of the Quraish chiefs on the one hand; and to console the Prophet (peace be upon him) and his companions
52,45,"So leave them alone until they encounter that Day of theirs when they shall be struck down,"
52,46,"when their stratagem shall be of no avail to them, nor shall they be succoured."
52,47,"Surely a chastisement awaits the wrong-doers even before the coming of that Day; but most of them do not know. {1}",footnotes:1:This is a repetition of the same theme that has already occurred in(Surah As-Sajdah
52,48,"Be patient, then, (O Prophet), until the judgement of your Lord comes. {1} For surely you are before Our eyes. {2} And celebrate the praise of your Lord when you rise, {3}",footnotes:1:That is
52,49,"and also celebrate His praise at night, {1} and at the retreat of the stars. {2}",footnotes:1:This implies the Maghrib
